{"title_page": "Portia de Rossi", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian actress married to comedian Ellen DeGeneres}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Portia de Rosiiiiiiiiiii\n| image              = PortiadeRossi Sept2012.jpg\n| caption            = Portia de Rossi in 2012\n| birth_name         = Amanda Lee Rogers\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1973|1|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Horsham, Victoria]], Australia\n| residence          = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Australian]], \n[[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = Portia Lee James DeGeneres\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| occupation         = Actress, model, philanthropist\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n\n| spouse             = \n{{marriage|Mel Metcalfe<!--- Do not link. Wikipedia has an article about a different Mel Metcalfe.---><br>|1996|1999|reason=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|[[Ellen DeGeneres]]<br>|2008}}\n}}\n\n'''Portia Lee James DeGeneres''' (born '''Amanda Lee Rogers'''; January 31, 1973), known professionally as '''Portia de Rossi''', is an Australian-American model, philanthropist, and actress. She is best known for starring as [[Nelle Porter]] on the American drama series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' (1998\u20132002), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], as [[Lindsay F\u00fcnke|Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on the American television sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019), and as Elizabeth North on the American [[political thriller]] series ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' (2014\u20132017).<ref>{{cite web|author=Samantha Highfill |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/07/23/portia-de-rossi-scandal |title=Portia de Rossi joins season 4 of 'Scandal' |website=Entertainment Weekly|date=2014-07-23 |accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/scandal-elizabeth-north-portia-de-rossi-dead-killed-1202391942/|title='Scandal' Star, Shonda Rhimes React to Major Death (SPOILERS)|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=21 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-bios/portia-de-rossi|accessdate=28 January 2009|title=Celebrity Bios: Portia de Rossi|publisher=Us Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Geelong's Portia Marries Ellen|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/08/18/17323_news.html|accessdate=28 January 2009|publisher=Geelong Advertiser|date=18 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nShe also portrayed [[Olivia Lord]] on the American television drama series ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' (2007\u20132009) and Veronica Palmer on the American television sitcom ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' (2009\u20132010). De Rossi is married to comedian, actress, and television host [[Ellen DeGeneres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPortia de Rossi, born Amanda Lee Rogers in [[Horsham, Victoria|Horsham]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi|title=Australian Actress: Portia de Rossi|author=London Academy of Media and Film TV|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301142048/http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi/|archivedate=1 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the daughter of Margaret, a medical receptionist, and Barry Rogers, part Jewish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/91/Portia-de-Rossi.html|title=Portia de Rossi profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Her father died when she was nine years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTw1MoscAk4|title=Portia de Rossi on Ellen|work=Youtube|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> She grew up in [[Grovedale, Victoria|Grovedale]], a suburb of [[Geelong]], Victoria, and modelled for print and TV commercials as a child. In 1988, at age 15, Rogers adopted the name Portia de Rossi, by which she remains best known. In 2005, she explained she had intended to reinvent herself, using the given name of [[Portia (Merchant of Venice)|Portia]], a character from [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Merchant of Venice]],'' and an Italian last name. She was educated at [[Geelong Grammar| Geelong Grammar School]] and the [[University of Melbourne]], where she studied law.<ref name=Advocate>{{cite web |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200735/http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |title=Portia heart & soul |last1=Kort |first1=Michele |date=29 August 2005 |website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |publisher=[[Here Media]] |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-date=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDe Rossi's first significant role was as a young and impressionable model in the Australian [[1994 in film|1994 film]] ''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]].'' Soon afterward, she moved to Los Angeles and won guest roles on several TV shows and a permanent role in ''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]],'' before landing a part in the film ''[[Scream 2]].'' During her time in the United States, de Rossi worked diligently to drop her Australian accent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/05/07/1052280317160.html|title=The Very Private Portia|work=The Age|location=Melbourne|date=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDe Rossi garnered international attention when she joined the main cast of ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' in 1998, playing lawyer Nelle Porter. She remained with the show until its end in 2002. In 2001, she starred in ''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]'' alongside [[Christian Slater]]. From 2003\u201306, de Rossi starred as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on [[Fox Television]]'s ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]].'' She next portrayed [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.]]'s wife, [[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]], in the made-for-TV movie ''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]'' in 2003.  That same year, she portrayed an Australian reporter who inspires a protest against [[Frank Sinatra]] during a concert tour in ''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]].''\n\nIn 2005 de Rossi portrayed Zela, a fortune-teller, in the Wes Craven thriller ''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]].'' From 2007\u20132008, de Rossi appeared in ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'s'' fifth season as [[Julia McNamara]]'s girlfriend, [[Olivia Lord]].\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, de Rossi played the high-strung and controlling Veronica Palmer on the ABC show ''[[Better Off Ted]].'' In 2011, she appeared in ''Better Off Ted'' cast member [[Malcolm Barrett (actor)|Malcolm Barrett]]'s music video for \"Revenge of the Nerds,\" spoofing her character of Veronica in a cameo alongside other cast members of the cancelled series.<ref>{{cite web| title =Better Off Ted cast reunites for Malcolm Barrett's hip-hop video| publisher =Zap2It.com| url =http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| accessdate =16 November 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133350/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| archivedate =10 January 2012| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Portia de Rossi.jpg|thumb|left|Rossi in 2007]]\nShe ranked 69th in ''[[Stuff (magazine)|Stuff]] Magazine's'' 100 Sexiest Women, 31 in ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''' Sexiest Women of 2003 list, and 24 in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'s'' 100 Sexiest Women List in 2004; in late 2006, the magazine ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' listed her as one of the hottest women of film and TV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hottest Women of...Film and TV!|date=1 January 2007|first=Mike|last=Errico|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516065116/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|archivedate=16 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May of 2007, she was featured as one of 100 Most Beautiful in a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' special edition. ''[[TV Guide]]'' included her and Ellen DeGeneres in their Power A-List couples in 2007.\n\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] had ordered a pilot for a new drama series ''The Smart One,'' one of whose executive producers was listed as Ellen DeGeneres, and which featured de Rossi in a leading role. The actress was to star as a \"brilliant and successful woman who begrudgingly goes to work for her less-brainy but more popular sister \u2013 a former beauty queen, weather girl and now big-city Mayor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one|title=ABC to air Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's \"The Smart One\"|publisher=Unreality TV|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206163932/http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one/|archivedate=6 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> But ''The Smart One'' was not picked up for the 2012-13 season.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nSix years after the series was canceled by Fox, filming for a revived fourth season of ''Arrested Development'' began on 7 August 2012, and de Rossi reprised her role as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]. This fourth season consisted of 15 new episodes, which debuted at the same time on Netflix on 26 May 2013. Each episode focused on one particular character, with de Rossi's Lindsay featured in Episode 3, \"Indian Takers,\" and Episode 8, \"Red Hairing,\" and also appearing in several other episodes of the season.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|5577}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ABC confirmed that de Rossi was joining season 4 of ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]],'' in the role of Elizabeth North.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/portia-de-rossi-scandal-1201268000|title=Portia de Rossi Joins 'Scandal' in 'Top Secret Arc'|publisher=Variety|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014|first=Nikara|last=Johns}}</ref> De Rossi joined ''Scandal'' in the fourth season in a recurring role, before being upped to a series regular for the fifth season. In April 2017, in season six, de Rossi's character, Elizabeth North, was killed off by a golf club attack. De Rossi herself made the decision to depart the ''Scandal'' series, saying, \"I am incredibly grateful for my time here at ''Scandal.'' I will miss playing Elizabeth North but I've made the decision to focus on a business opportunity. Shonda, Betsy and the cast have been incredibly supportive of my decision. I will always love my ''Scandal'' family. I'll be watching!\" Creator Shonda Rhimes added, \"I have been a fan of Portia's for years and it was an honor to have her join our ''Scandal'' family.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, de Rossi announced on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' that she would be retiring from acting, though she later elaborated that she would make an exception for future seasons of ''Arrested Development''.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4212133/portia-de-rossi-quit-acting/ Portia de Rossi confirms on \u2018Ellen\u2019 that she has decided to quit acting]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IlXvP0O4cfw Portia de Rossi Talks What's Next After Acting]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:PortiadeRossiEllenDeGeneresHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|upright|De Rossi and her wife, Ellen DeGeneres, in September 2012]]\nDe Rossi was married to documentary film-maker Mel Metcalfe, from 1996 to 1999, initially part of a plan to get a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]], though she did not go through with the plan. She said about the marriage that \"it just obviously wasn't right for me.\"<ref name=Advocate/> In a 2010 interview on ''[[Good Morning America]],'' she explained that as a young actress, she was fearful of being exposed as a lesbian.<ref name=\"gmabook\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/portia-de-rossi-reveals-depths-eating-disorders-book/story?id=12033594|title=Portia de Rossi: 'I Would Starve Myself Daily'|date=3 November 2010|publisher=ABC News|author=Olivia Katrandjian|accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, de Rossi dated director [[Francesca Gregorini]], the daughter of [[Barbara Bach]] and the stepdaughter of [[Ringo Starr]]. She said that most of her family and ''Ally McBeal'' castmates did not know she was a lesbian until tabloid pictures of the couple were published.<ref name=Advocate/> She declined to publicly discuss the relationship or her sexual orientation at the time.\n\nDe Rossi and Gregorini broke up in late 2004 because de Rossi began dating DeGeneres, whom she met backstage at an awards show. In 2005, she opened up publicly about her sexual orientation in interviews with ''[[Details (magazine)|Details]]'' and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' She and DeGeneres became engaged when DeGeneres proposed in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-road-to-romance-2012261|title=Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's Road to Romance |date=26 January 2012|first=Zach|last=Johnson|work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> They were married at their Beverly Hills home on 16 August 2008, witnessed by their mothers and 17 other guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2580530/Television-presenter-Ellen-DeGeneres-marries-lesbian-lover-Portia-de-Rossi.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Television presenter Ellen DeGeneres marries lesbian lover Portia de Rossi|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> On 6 August 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres.<ref name=\"TMZnamechange\">{{cite web|last=TMZ Staff|title=Portia to Ellen: I Want to Be a DeGeneres!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/08/09/ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-name-change-petition-married-gay-marriage|work=[[TMZ.com|TMZ]]|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> The petition was granted on 23 September 2010.<ref name=Yahoo.com>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi takes wife Ellen DeGeneres' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2010-09-23-derossi-name-change_N.htm|work=USA Today|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> She became a United States citizen in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2011/09/portia_becomes_a_us_citizen_0915.php|title=Portia Becomes a U.S. Citizen!|publisher=Ellen.warnerbros.com|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, de Rossi published her autobiography, titled ''Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain,'' within which she wrote about the turmoil that she had experienced in her life, including suffering from [[anorexia nervosa]] and [[bulimia]] and being misdiagnosed with [[lupus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rossi|first=Portia|title=Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain|publisher=Atria|date=November 2010|isbn=1-4391-7778-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unbearablelightn00dero}}</ref> She had struggled with the [[eating disorders]] for four years while filming ''Ally McBeal.''<ref name=Vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com|title= Disappearing Act: How did Portia de Rossi withstand the pressures of Hollywood.|accessdate=22 March 2009|last=Van Meter|first=Jonathan|publisher=Vogue|archiveurl=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15043182_ITM|archivedate= 1 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi nips at new TV challenges|first=Donna|last=Freydkin|work=USA Today|date=13 November 2007|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-11-12-portia-de-rossi_N.htm}}</ref> To promote the book, she appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''\n \nDeGeneres and de Rossi both became vegans in 2008, though DeGeneres stated that she is no longer vegan.  They have adopted several rescue animals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juliette Steen |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2016/04/29/famous-vegans-and-vegetarians-some-of-these-celebrities-might-s/ |title=Famous Vegans And Vegetarians (Some Of These Celebrities Might Surprise You) |website=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=29 April 2016|accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|title=A Heart for Animals: Ellen DeGeneres & Portia de Rossi on The Celebrity Spot|date=25 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025051112/http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|archivedate=25 October 2014|df=dmy-all|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, de Rossi tweeted that actor [[Steven Seagal]] exposed himself to her while she was auditioning for one of his films.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi: Steven Seagal Sexually Harassed Me During an Audition|first=Tracy E.|last=Gilchrest|work=The Advocate|date=8 November 2017|url=https://www.advocate.com/women/2017/11/08/portia-de-rossi-steven-segal-sexually-harassed-me-during-audition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41936741|title=Portia de Rossi accuses Steven Seagal of sexual harassment|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nDe Rossi supports a variety of charitable organizations, including [[Locks of Love]], a group that provides human hair wigs (made from donated ponytails) either free of charge or on a sliding scale based on their own guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac5|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Aa8|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|title=Charity Review of Locks of Love|publisher=Charityreports.give.org|accessdate=12 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307045743/http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|archivedate=7 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/charity-reviews/national/children-and-youth/locks-of-love-in-lake-worth-fl-1839|title=BBB review of Locks of Love|publisher=Bbb.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> for children with [[alopecia]] and other medical conditions that cause [[hair loss]], such as chemotherapy for certain types of [[cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac2|title=Locks of Love FAQ|publisher=Locksoflove.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe has also supported fundraising efforts for [[FXB International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2006/07/portia-de-rossi-helps-fxb-to-rebuild.html|title=Portia de Rossi Helps FXB to Rebuild Uganda|work=Celebrity Halo|date=July 2006|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|African AIDS]] relief organization, and The Art of Elysium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2008/01/portia-de-rossi-supports-art-of-elysium.html|title=Portia de Rossi supports The Art of Elysium|work=Celebrity Halo|date=January 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an art foundation for terminally ill children. An avid animal lover, de Rossi also supports [[Alley Cat Allies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|title=I'm an Alley Cat Ally \u2013 Portia de Rossi|accessdate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120045419/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|archivedate=20 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an organization dedicated to protecting and improving the lives of cats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523010128/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 May 2009|title=Alley Cat Allies \u2013 About Us|accessdate=29 September 2010}}</ref> De Rossi and DeGeneres are strong supporters of [[The Gentle Barn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gentlebarn.org|title=The Gentle Barn|publisher=gentlebarn.org|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> a California sanctuary for abused animals.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]]''\n|Giddy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''The Woman in the Moon''\n|Shauna\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Scream 2]]''\n|Sorority Sister Murphy\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Girl (1998 film)|Girl]]''\n|Carla Sparrow\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''The Invisibles''\n|Joy\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[American Intellectuals]]''\n|Sarah\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Stigmata (film)|Stigmata]]''\n|Jennifer Kelliho\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Women in Film''\n|Gina\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]''\n|Tess Donnelly\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Two Girls from Leemore''\n|Blind Woman\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[I Witness]]''\n|Emily Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]]''\n|Hilary Hunter\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dead & Breakfast]]''\n|Kelly\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]]''\n|Zela\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Shift''\n|Denise Moore\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |title=About the Cast of THE SHIFT (2009) - movie starring Dr. Wayne Dyer |publisher=Dyermovie.com |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222030536/http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Unity (film)|Unity]]''\n|Narrator\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Now Add Honey]]''\n|Beth Halloway\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1995\u20131996\n|''[[Too Something]]''\n|Maria Hunter\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1996\u20131997\n|''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]]''\n|Elana Lewis\n|Main cast; 22 episodes\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Veronica's Closet]]''\n|Carolyn\n| Episode: \"Veronica's First Date\"\n|-\n|1998\n|''Astoria''\n|\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\n|''A Breed Apart''\n|Lana Collins\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|1998\u20132002\n|''[[Ally McBeal]]''\n|[[Nelle Porter]]\n|Main cast; 89 episodes\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Ally (sitcom)|Ally]]''\n|Nelle Porter\n|Main cast; 12 episodes; ''Ally McBeal'' spin-off\n|-\n|2002\n|''The Glow''\n|Jackie Lawrence\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[The Twilight Zone (2002 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''\n|Laurel Janus\n| Episode: \"[[Dead Man's Eyes (The Twilight Zone)|Dead Man's Eyes]]\"\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]''\n|[[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]]\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Mister Sterling]]''\n|Lauren Barnes\n|2 episodes: \"Wish List\" and \"Final Passage\"\n|-\n|2003\u20132006,<br>2013,<br>2018-2019\n|''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]''\n|[[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]\n|Main cast; 70 episodes\n|-\n|2007\u20132009\n|''[[Nip/Tuck]]''\n|[[Olivia Lord]]\n|Recurring cast (Season 5); 10 episodes\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|''[[Better Off Ted]]''\n|Veronica Palmer\n|Main cast; 26 episodes\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Mockingbird Lane]]''\n|Lily Munster\n| Pilot\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Sean Saves the World]]''\n|Jill\n| Episode: \"The Joy of Ex\"\n|-\n|2014\u20132017\n|''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''\n|Elizabeth North\n|Recurring (Season 4), Main cast (Seasons 5\u20136)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2015/05/14/scandal-season-5-cast-portia-de-rossi-liz-chief-of-staff/|title='Scandal' Season 5 Cast: Portia de Ross a Series Regular, Liz Chief of Staff&nbsp;\u2013 TVLine|author=Michael Ausiello|date=|work=TVLine|accessdate=29 August 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''\n| Dr. Wolf \n| 2 episodes: \"The Book!\" and \"Baka, Bile and Baseball Bats\"\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Family Guy]]''\n| Bonnie Swanson (prank call voice)\n| Episode: \"A House Full of Peters\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Award\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Category\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Work\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Result\n|-\n|1999\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[5th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|rowspan=3|''Ally McBeal''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2000\n|[[6th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2001\n|[[7th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Calista Flockhart]], [[Courtney Thorne-Smith]], [[Greg Germann]], [[Lisa Nicole Carson]], [[Jane Krakowski]], [[Vonda Shepard]], [[Lucy Liu]], [[Peter MacNicol]], and [[Gil Bellows]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2004\n|[[TV Land Award]]\n|Future Classic Award <small> Shared with [[Jason Bateman]], [[Will Arnett]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jessica Walter]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Mitchell Hurwitz|Mitchell Hurwitz (executive producer)]], and [[David Nevins (television producer)|David Nevins (executive producer)]] </small>\n|rowspan=6|''Arrested Development''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Satellite Award|Golden Satellite Award]]\n|[[8th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Supporting Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2005\n|[[9th Golden Satellite Awards#Best Actress - Musical or Comedy Series|Best Actress in a Series, Comedy or Musical]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|[[11th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2006\n|[[12th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], and [[Jessica Walters]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2014\n|[[20th Screen Actors Guild Awards#Television|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] <small> Shared with [[Will Arnett]], [[Jason Bateman]], [[John Beard (news anchor)|John Beard]], [[Michael Cera]], [[David Cross]], [[Isla Fisher]], [[Tony Hale]], [[Ron Howard]], [[Liza Minnelli]], [[Alia Shawkat]], [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Jessica Walter]], and [[Henry Winkler]] </small>\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q215366|c=Category:Portia de Rossi|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=nO|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0005577}}\n* {{Amg name|198456}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Portia de Rossi\n|list =\n{{Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVComedy 1994\u20131999}}\n}}\n{{Ellen DeGeneres}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:De Rossi, Portia}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Australian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Australian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from California]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:People from Geelong]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:People from Horsham, Victoria]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Melbourne Girls Grammar]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian actress married to comedian Ellen DeGeneres}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Portia de Rossi\n| image              = PortiadeRossi Sept2012.jpg\n| caption            = Portia de Rossi in 2012\n| birth_name         = Amanda Lee Rogers\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1973|1|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Horsham, Victoria]], Australia\n| residence          = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| nationality        = [[Australian]], \n[[United States|American]]\n| other_names        = Portia Lee James DeGeneres\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| occupation         = Actress, model, philanthropist\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present\n\n| spouse             = \n{{marriage|Mel Metcalfe<!--- Do not link. Wikipedia has an article about a different Mel Metcalfe.---><br>|1996|1999|reason=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|[[Ellen DeGeneres]]<br>|2008}}\n}}\n\n'''Portia Lee James DeGeneres''' (born '''Amanda Lee Rogers'''; January 31, 1973), known professionally as '''Portia de Rossi''', is an Australian-American model, philanthropist, and actress. She is best known for starring as [[Nelle Porter]] on the American drama series ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' (1998\u20132002), for which she won a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], as [[Lindsay F\u00fcnke|Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on the American television sitcom ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' (2003\u20132006, 2013, 2018\u20132019), and as Elizabeth North on the American [[political thriller]] series ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]'' (2014\u20132017).<ref>{{cite web|author=Samantha Highfill |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/07/23/portia-de-rossi-scandal |title=Portia de Rossi joins season 4 of 'Scandal' |website=Entertainment Weekly|date=2014-07-23 |accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/scandal-elizabeth-north-portia-de-rossi-dead-killed-1202391942/|title='Scandal' Star, Shonda Rhimes React to Major Death (SPOILERS)|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister|date=21 April 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-bios/portia-de-rossi|accessdate=28 January 2009|title=Celebrity Bios: Portia de Rossi|publisher=Us Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Geelong's Portia Marries Ellen|url=http://www.geelongadvertiser.com.au/article/2008/08/18/17323_news.html|accessdate=28 January 2009|publisher=Geelong Advertiser|date=18 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nShe also portrayed [[Olivia Lord]] on the American television drama series ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' (2007\u20132009) and Veronica Palmer on the American television sitcom ''[[Better Off Ted]]'' (2009\u20132010). De Rossi is married to comedian, actress, and television host [[Ellen DeGeneres]].\n\n==Early life==\nPortia de Rossi, born Amanda Lee Rogers in [[Horsham, Victoria|Horsham]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi|title=Australian Actress: Portia de Rossi|author=London Academy of Media and Film TV|accessdate=24 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301142048/http://www.media-courses.com/blog/australian-actress-portia-de-rossi/|archivedate=1 March 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is the daughter of Margaret, a medical receptionist, and Barry Rogers, part Jewish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/91/Portia-de-Rossi.html|title=Portia de Rossi profile|publisher=Filmreference.com|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Her father died when she was nine years old.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTw1MoscAk4|title=Portia de Rossi on Ellen|work=Youtube|accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref> She grew up in [[Grovedale, Victoria|Grovedale]], a suburb of [[Geelong]], Victoria, and modelled for print and TV commercials as a child. In 1988, at age 15, Rogers adopted the name Portia de Rossi, by which she remains best known. In 2005, she explained she had intended to reinvent herself, using the given name of [[Portia (Merchant of Venice)|Portia]], a character from [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[The Merchant of Venice]],'' and an Italian last name. She was educated at [[Geelong Grammar| Geelong Grammar School]] and the [[University of Melbourne]], where she studied law.<ref name=Advocate>{{cite web |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526200735/http://www.advocate.com/politics/commentary/2005/08/29/portia-heart-amp-soul |title=Portia heart & soul |last1=Kort |first1=Michele |date=29 August 2005 |website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |publisher=[[Here Media]] |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-date=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDe Rossi's first significant role was as a young and impressionable model in the Australian [[1994 in film|1994 film]] ''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]].'' Soon afterward, she moved to Los Angeles and won guest roles on several TV shows and a permanent role in ''[[Nick Freno: Licensed Teacher]],'' before landing a part in the film ''[[Scream 2]].'' During her time in the United States, de Rossi worked diligently to drop her Australian accent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/05/07/1052280317160.html|title=The Very Private Portia|work=The Age|location=Melbourne|date=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDe Rossi garnered international attention when she joined the main cast of ''[[Ally McBeal]]'' in 1998, playing lawyer Nelle Porter. She remained with the show until its end in 2002. In 2001, she starred in ''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]'' alongside [[Christian Slater]]. From 2003\u201306, de Rossi starred as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]] on [[Fox Television]]'s ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]].'' She next portrayed [[John F. Kennedy, Jr.]]'s wife, [[Carolyn Bessette-Kennedy]], in the made-for-TV movie ''[[America's Prince: The John F. Kennedy Jr. Story]]'' in 2003.  That same year, she portrayed an Australian reporter who inspires a protest against [[Frank Sinatra]] during a concert tour in ''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]].''\n\nIn 2005 de Rossi portrayed Zela, a fortune-teller, in the Wes Craven thriller ''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]].'' From 2007\u20132008, de Rossi appeared in ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'s'' fifth season as [[Julia McNamara]]'s girlfriend, [[Olivia Lord]].\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, de Rossi played the high-strung and controlling Veronica Palmer on the ABC show ''[[Better Off Ted]].'' In 2011, she appeared in ''Better Off Ted'' cast member [[Malcolm Barrett (actor)|Malcolm Barrett]]'s music video for \"Revenge of the Nerds,\" spoofing her character of Veronica in a cameo alongside other cast members of the cancelled series.<ref>{{cite web| title =Better Off Ted cast reunites for Malcolm Barrett's hip-hop video| publisher =Zap2It.com| url =http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| accessdate =16 November 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133350/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/07/better-off-ted-cast-reunites-for-malcolm-barretts-hip-hop-video.html| archivedate =10 January 2012| df =dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Portia de Rossi.jpg|thumb|left|Rossi in 2007]]\nShe ranked 69th in ''[[Stuff (magazine)|Stuff]] Magazine's'' 100 Sexiest Women, 31 in ''[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]]''' Sexiest Women of 2003 list, and 24 in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'s'' 100 Sexiest Women List in 2004; in late 2006, the magazine ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' listed her as one of the hottest women of film and TV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hottest Women of...Film and TV!|date=1 January 2007|first=Mike|last=Errico|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070516065116/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?ID=2464&src=blender_ed|archivedate=16 May 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In May of 2007, she was featured as one of 100 Most Beautiful in a ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' special edition. ''[[TV Guide]]'' included her and Ellen DeGeneres in their Power A-List couples in 2007.\n\nIn February 2012, it was announced that [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] had ordered a pilot for a new drama series ''The Smart One,'' one of whose executive producers was listed as Ellen DeGeneres, and which featured de Rossi in a leading role. The actress was to star as a \"brilliant and successful woman who begrudgingly goes to work for her less-brainy but more popular sister \u2013 a former beauty queen, weather girl and now big-city Mayor.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one|title=ABC to air Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's \"The Smart One\"|publisher=Unreality TV|date=6 February 2012|accessdate=6 February 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206163932/http://spoilerville.unrealitytv.com/abc-to-air-ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-the-smart-one/|archivedate=6 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> But ''The Smart One'' was not picked up for the 2012-13 season.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\nSix years after the series was canceled by Fox, filming for a revived fourth season of ''Arrested Development'' began on 7 August 2012, and de Rossi reprised her role as [[Lindsay Bluth F\u00fcnke]]. This fourth season consisted of 15 new episodes, which debuted at the same time on Netflix on 26 May 2013. Each episode focused on one particular character, with de Rossi's Lindsay featured in Episode 3, \"Indian Takers,\" and Episode 8, \"Red Hairing,\" and also appearing in several other episodes of the season.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|5577}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, ABC confirmed that de Rossi was joining season 4 of ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]],'' in the role of Elizabeth North.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/portia-de-rossi-scandal-1201268000|title=Portia de Rossi Joins 'Scandal' in 'Top Secret Arc'|publisher=Variety|date=23 July 2014|accessdate=24 July 2014|first=Nikara|last=Johns}}</ref> De Rossi joined ''Scandal'' in the fourth season in a recurring role, before being upped to a series regular for the fifth season. In April 2017, in season six, de Rossi's character, Elizabeth North, was killed off by a golf club attack. De Rossi herself made the decision to depart the ''Scandal'' series, saying, \"I am incredibly grateful for my time here at ''Scandal.'' I will miss playing Elizabeth North but I've made the decision to focus on a business opportunity. Shonda, Betsy and the cast have been incredibly supportive of my decision. I will always love my ''Scandal'' family. I'll be watching!\" Creator Shonda Rhimes added, \"I have been a fan of Portia's for years and it was an honor to have her join our ''Scandal'' family.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn May 2018, de Rossi announced on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' that she would be retiring from acting, though she later elaborated that she would make an exception for future seasons of ''Arrested Development''.<ref>[https://globalnews.ca/news/4212133/portia-de-rossi-quit-acting/ Portia de Rossi confirms on \u2018Ellen\u2019 that she has decided to quit acting]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IlXvP0O4cfw Portia de Rossi Talks What's Next After Acting]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:PortiadeRossiEllenDeGeneresHWOFSept2012.jpg|thumb|right|upright|De Rossi and her wife, Ellen DeGeneres, in September 2012]]\nDe Rossi was married to documentary film-maker Mel Metcalfe, from 1996 to 1999, initially part of a plan to get a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]], though she did not go through with the plan. She said about the marriage that \"it just obviously wasn't right for me.\"<ref name=Advocate/> In a 2010 interview on ''[[Good Morning America]],'' she explained that as a young actress, she was fearful of being exposed as a lesbian.<ref name=\"gmabook\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/portia-de-rossi-reveals-depths-eating-disorders-book/story?id=12033594|title=Portia de Rossi: 'I Would Starve Myself Daily'|date=3 November 2010|publisher=ABC News|author=Olivia Katrandjian|accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, de Rossi dated director [[Francesca Gregorini]], the daughter of [[Barbara Bach]] and the stepdaughter of [[Ringo Starr]]. She said that most of her family and ''Ally McBeal'' castmates did not know she was a lesbian until tabloid pictures of the couple were published.<ref name=Advocate/> She declined to publicly discuss the relationship or her sexual orientation at the time.\n\nDe Rossi and Gregorini broke up in late 2004 because de Rossi began dating DeGeneres, whom she met backstage at an awards show. In 2005, she opened up publicly about her sexual orientation in interviews with ''[[Details (magazine)|Details]]'' and ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]].'' She and DeGeneres became engaged when DeGeneres proposed in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/ellen-degeneres-and-portia-de-rossis-road-to-romance-2012261|title=Ellen DeGeneres and Portia de Rossi's Road to Romance |date=26 January 2012|first=Zach|last=Johnson|work=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> They were married at their Beverly Hills home on 16 August 2008, witnessed by their mothers and 17 other guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2580530/Television-presenter-Ellen-DeGeneres-marries-lesbian-lover-Portia-de-Rossi.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|title=Television presenter Ellen DeGeneres marries lesbian lover Portia de Rossi|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> On 6 August 2010, de Rossi filed a petition to legally change her name to Portia Lee James DeGeneres.<ref name=\"TMZnamechange\">{{cite web|last=TMZ Staff|title=Portia to Ellen: I Want to Be a DeGeneres!|url=http://www.tmz.com/2010/08/09/ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-name-change-petition-married-gay-marriage|work=[[TMZ.com|TMZ]]|accessdate=11 August 2010}}</ref> The petition was granted on 23 September 2010.<ref name=Yahoo.com>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi takes wife Ellen DeGeneres' name|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2010-09-23-derossi-name-change_N.htm|work=USA Today|date=23 September 2010}}</ref> She became a United States citizen in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2011/09/portia_becomes_a_us_citizen_0915.php|title=Portia Becomes a U.S. Citizen!|publisher=Ellen.warnerbros.com|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, de Rossi published her autobiography, titled ''Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain,'' within which she wrote about the turmoil that she had experienced in her life, including suffering from [[anorexia nervosa]] and [[bulimia]] and being misdiagnosed with [[lupus]].<ref>{{cite book|last=de Rossi|first=Portia|title=Unbearable Lightness: A Story of Loss and Gain|publisher=Atria|date=November 2010|isbn=1-4391-7778-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unbearablelightn00dero}}</ref> She had struggled with the [[eating disorders]] for four years while filming ''Ally McBeal.''<ref name=Vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com|title= Disappearing Act: How did Portia de Rossi withstand the pressures of Hollywood.|accessdate=22 March 2009|last=Van Meter|first=Jonathan|publisher=Vogue|archiveurl=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-15043182_ITM|archivedate= 1 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi nips at new TV challenges|first=Donna|last=Freydkin|work=USA Today|date=13 November 2007|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2007-11-12-portia-de-rossi_N.htm}}</ref> To promote the book, she appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]].''\n \nDeGeneres and de Rossi both became vegans in 2008, though DeGeneres stated that she is no longer vegan.  They have adopted several rescue animals.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juliette Steen |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com.au/2016/04/29/famous-vegans-and-vegetarians-some-of-these-celebrities-might-s/ |title=Famous Vegans And Vegetarians (Some Of These Celebrities Might Surprise You) |website=Huffingtonpost.com.au |date=29 April 2016|accessdate=2017-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|title=A Heart for Animals: Ellen DeGeneres & Portia de Rossi on The Celebrity Spot|date=25 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025051112/http://barkandswagger.com/a-heart-for-animals-ellen-degeneres-portia-de-rossi-celebrity-spot|archivedate=25 October 2014|df=dmy-all|accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, de Rossi tweeted that actor [[Steven Seagal]] exposed himself to her while she was auditioning for one of his films.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Portia de Rossi: Steven Seagal Sexually Harassed Me During an Audition|first=Tracy E.|last=Gilchrest|work=The Advocate|date=8 November 2017|url=https://www.advocate.com/women/2017/11/08/portia-de-rossi-steven-segal-sexually-harassed-me-during-audition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41936741|title=Portia de Rossi accuses Steven Seagal of sexual harassment|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=9 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nDe Rossi supports a variety of charitable organizations, including [[Locks of Love]], a group that provides human hair wigs (made from donated ponytails) either free of charge or on a sliding scale based on their own guidelines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac5|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Aa8|title=Locks of Love|publisher=Locks of Love|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|title=Charity Review of Locks of Love|publisher=Charityreports.give.org|accessdate=12 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070307045743/http://charityreports.give.org/Public/Report.aspx?CharityID=1839|archivedate=7 March 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbb.org/charity-reviews/national/children-and-youth/locks-of-love-in-lake-worth-fl-1839|title=BBB review of Locks of Love|publisher=Bbb.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> for children with [[alopecia]] and other medical conditions that cause [[hair loss]], such as chemotherapy for certain types of [[cancer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.locksoflove.org/faq.html#Ac2|title=Locks of Love FAQ|publisher=Locksoflove.org|accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nShe has also supported fundraising efforts for [[FXB International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2006/07/portia-de-rossi-helps-fxb-to-rebuild.html|title=Portia de Rossi Helps FXB to Rebuild Uganda|work=Celebrity Halo|date=July 2006|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an [[HIV/AIDS in Africa|African AIDS]] relief organization, and The Art of Elysium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celebrityhalo.blogspot.com/2008/01/portia-de-rossi-supports-art-of-elysium.html|title=Portia de Rossi supports The Art of Elysium|work=Celebrity Halo|date=January 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008}}</ref> an art foundation for terminally ill children. An avid animal lover, de Rossi also supports [[Alley Cat Allies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|title=I'm an Alley Cat Ally \u2013 Portia de Rossi|accessdate=29 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120045419/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=739|archivedate=20 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> an organization dedicated to protecting and improving the lives of cats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523010128/http://www.alleycat.org/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=616|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 May 2009|title=Alley Cat Allies \u2013 About Us|accessdate=29 September 2010}}</ref> De Rossi and DeGeneres are strong supporters of [[The Gentle Barn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gentlebarn.org|title=The Gentle Barn|publisher=gentlebarn.org|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> a California sanctuary for abused animals.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!-- do not add rowspans to this table, it breaks sorting -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Sirens (1994 film)|Sirens]]''\n|Giddy\n|\n|-\n|1995\n|''The Woman in the Moon''\n|Shauna\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Scream 2]]''\n|Sorority Sister Murphy\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Girl (1998 film)|Girl]]''\n|Carla Sparrow\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''The Invisibles''\n|Joy\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[American Intellectuals]]''\n|Sarah\n|\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Stigmata (film)|Stigmata]]''\n|Jennifer Kelliho\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''Women in Film''\n|Gina\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[Who Is Cletis Tout?]]''\n|Tess Donnelly\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''Two Girls from Leemore''\n|Blind Woman\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[I Witness]]''\n|Emily Thompson\n|\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[The Night We Called It a Day (film)|The Night We Called It a Day]]''\n|Hilary Hunter\n|\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dead & Breakfast]]''\n|Kelly\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Cursed (2005 film)|Cursed]]''\n|Zela\n|\n|-\n|2009\n|''The Shift''\n|Denise Moore\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |title=About the Cast of THE SHIFT (2009) - movie starring Dr. Wayne Dyer |publisher=Dyermovie.com |accessdate=16 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222030536/http://www.dyermovie.com/about/cast |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Unity (film)|Unity]]''\n|Narrator\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Now Add Honey]]''\n|Beth Halloway\n|\n|}\n\n===Television